{{Use American English|date=July 2018}}{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}

'''Alan Lee Berman''' (born October 7, 1943)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://catalogue.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb13746961r|title=BnF Catalogue général|last=|first=|date=|website=catalogue.bnf.fr|language=fr|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-23}}</ref> also known as '''Lanny Berman''', is an American psychologist, psychotherapist, and suicidologist. He is an Adjunct Professor of Psychiatry and Behavioral Sciences at [[Johns Hopkins School of Medicine]]. Berman was formerly the Executive Director of the [[American Association of Suicidology]]. He is a fellow of the [[American Psychological Association]]. Berman has a private practice in psychological and forensic consultation. 

== Education ==
Berman earned a Bachelor of Arts degree from [[Johns Hopkins University]] and a Doctor of Philosophy from [[Catholic University of America]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uwlax.edu/globalassets/academics/conted/suicide-prevention/pdfs/lanny-berman-bio.pdf|title=BIO: DR. ALAN L. BERMAN (LANNY)|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Wisconsin La Crosse|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> His 1970 dissertation was titled ''The Effect Of Videotape Self-Confrontation On Level Of Ego Functioning And Thought Disturbance In Non-Paranoid, Process Schizophrenics''.<ref>{{Cite thesis|last=Berman|first=Alan L|title=The effect of videotape self-confrontation on level of ego functioning and thought disturbance in non-paranoid, process schizophrenics|date=1970|degree=|publisher=|url=http://psycnet.apa.org/fulltext/1973-02793-001.pdf|doi=|language=English}}</ref>

== Career ==
Berman worked at [[American University]] from 1969 to 1991, eventually becoming a tenured full professor. He served as the president of the American Association of Suicidology from 1984 to 1985. After 1991, he became a Distinguished Adjunct Professor at American University. The same year, he was named the director of the National Center for the Study and Prevention of Suicide at the Washington School of Psychiatry. In January 1995, Berman became the Executive Director of the [[American Association of Suicidology]]. He retired from that position on July 1, 2014. In 2009 and 2011, he was elected the president of the [[International Association for Suicide Prevention]]. Berman is an Adjunct Professor of Psychiatry and Behavioral Sciences at [[Johns Hopkins School of Medicine]].<ref name=":0" />

Berman is a Diplomate in Clinical Psychology from the American Board of Professional Psychology. He is a fellow of the [[American Psychological Association]] and the [[International Academy of Suicide Research]].<ref name=":0" /> Berman was the doctoral advisor of [[Michael Hendricks]].<ref>{{Cite thesis|last=Hendricks|first=Michael Lawrence|title=The occurrence of suicidal ideation over the course of HIV infection in gay men: a cross-sectional study|date=1993|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/occurrence-of-suicidal-ideation-over-the-course-of-hiv-infection-in-gay-men-a-cross-sectional-study/oclc/34135687|language=English}}</ref> Berman has a private practice in psychological and forensic consultation in [[Chevy Chase, Maryland|Chevy Chase]], [[Maryland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jhsph.edu/departments/mental-health/centers/suicide-prevention/related-faculty/index.html|title=Related Faculty|last=|first=|date=|website=Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-23}}</ref>

== Awards and honors ==
In 1982, Berman received the Shneidman Award for Outstanding Contributions in Research in Suicidology. In 2006, he received the Louis I. Dublin Award for service and contributions to the field of suicide prevention.<ref name=":0" />

