'''Hortense Aka-Anghui''' (December 18, 1933 – September 30, 2017) was an [[Ivory Coast|Ivorian]] politician.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.linfodrome.com/vie-politique/34085-le-pdci-en-deuil-hortense-aka-anghui-maire-de-port-bouet-est-decedee |title=Le Pdci en deuil : Hortense Aka Anghui, maire de Port-Bouët, est décédée |date=2017-09-30 |language=fr-fr |access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref>
Born '''Hortense Dadié''' in [[Agboville]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alerte-info.net/alerte_details.php?f=3941|title=Alerte Infos :: Au "royaume" de Port-Bouët à Abidjan, la "reine" se nomme Aka Anghui (BIO-PORTRAIT)|website=alerte-info.net|accessdate=29 September 2017}}</ref> Aka-Anghui is the sister of [[Bernard Dadié]].<ref name="Daddieh2016">{{cite book|author=Cyril K. Daddieh|title=Historical Dictionary of Cote d'Ivoire (The Ivory Coast)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_VptCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA70|date=9 February 2016|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-8108-7389-6|pages=70–}}</ref> She was elected to the [[National Assembly (Ivory Coast)|National Assembly]] as a member of the [[Democratic Party of Côte d'Ivoire – African Democratic Rally]] in [[Ivorian general election, 1965|1965]], later serving as vice-president of the Assembly and remaining a member until 1990;<ref name="hortenseaka-anghui.ci">{{cite web|url=http://hortenseaka-anghui.ci/haa.php|title=Hortense AKA-ANGUI|website=hortenseaka-anghui.ci|accessdate=29 September 2017}}</ref> with [[Gladys Anoma]] and [[Jeanne Gervais]] she was one of the first women elected to that body.<ref name="Sheldon2005">{{cite book|author=Kathleen E. Sheldon|title=Historical Dictionary of Women in Sub-Saharan Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=36BViNOAu3sC|year=2005|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-5331-7}}</ref> From 1980 until 2017 she served as mayor of [[Port-Bouët]].<ref name="hortenseaka-anghui.ci"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ivoiretimes.com/politique/mairie-de-port-bouet-plus-de-30-ans-apres-voici-le-successeur-de-hortense-aka-anghui/|title=Mairie de Port-Bouët/ Plus de 30 ans après: Voici le successeur de Hortense Aka Anghui - Ivoire Times|first=|last=PREMITICA|date=31 July 2017|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2017}}</ref> She also served as the [[Ministry of Women's Affairs (Ivory Coast)|Minister for Women's Affairs]] from 1986 to 1990, and from 1984 until 1991 as president of the [[Association des Femmes Ivoriennes]]. She has served as well as a member of the Central Committee and the Political Bureau of her political party. Aka-Anghui trained as a [[pharmacist]], earning a doctorate from the [[University of Paris]] in 1961, and operated a pharmacy and medical laboratory in [[Treichville]], in which town she had been raised, prior to entering politics.<ref name="Daddieh2016"/>
